The strength of Newton's method is on root finding. We're asked to
approximate

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}x=2^{1/6}\end{align*}

which we can write as a root finding problem,

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}x^6-2=0.\end{align*}

With this in mind, let

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}f(x) = x^6-2.\end{align*}

Taking the derivative gives

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}f'(x) = 6x^5.\end{align*}

We start with $x_1=1$ as our first iteration and so if we apply Newton's
Method, we get,

\begin{align*}x_{2} = x_{1} - \frac{f(x_{1})}{f'(x_{1})} = 1 - \frac{f(1)}{f'(1)} = 1 - \frac{-1}{6} = 1+\frac{1}{6} = \frac{7}{6}.\end{align*}

If we actually compute $2^{1/6}$ we get

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}2^{1/6}\approx{}1.122462048\end{align*}

and so $\frac{7}{6}=1.166666667$ is already in good agreement.
